{:questions [{:id "U3-PC-FRQ-Q01" :type "free-response" :prompt "Researchers are investigating whether people who exercise with a training partner have a greater increase, on average, in targeted exercise intensity compared with people who exercise alone. Two methods of collecting data have been proposed.\n\nMethod I: Recruit volunteers who are willing to participate. Randomly assign each participant to exercise with a training partner or to exercise alone.\n\nMethod II: Select a random sample of people from all the people who exercise at a community fitness center. Ask each person in the sample whether they use a training partner, and use the response to create the two groups.\n\n(a) For each method, the researchers will record the change in targeted exercise intensity for each person in the investigation. They will compare the mean change in intensity between those who exercise with a training partner and those who do not.\n\n(i) Describe the population of generalization if method I is used. Explain your answer.\n\n(ii) Describe the population of generalization if method II is used. Explain your answer.\n\n(b) Suppose the investigation produces a result that is statistically significant using both methods. What can be concluded if method I is used that cannot be concluded if method II is used? Explain your answer." :solution {:parts [{:part-id "a-i" :description "Describe the population of generalization if method I is used. Explain your answer." :response "For method I, the results of the study apply to the volunteers and can only be generalized to the population of all people who would volunteer to participate in an exercise intensity study, because there is not random selection from a population of interest."} {:part-id "a-ii" :description "Describe the population of generalization if method II is used. Explain your answer." :response "For method II, the results of the study can be generalized to all people who exercise at the community fitness center, because the sample was selected at random from all the people who exercise at a community fitness center."} {:part-id "b" :description "Suppose the investigation produces a result that is statistically significant using both methods. What can be concluded if method I is used that cannot be concluded if method II is used? Explain your answer." :response "With method I, the researchers will be able to conclude that exercising with a training partner causes a greater increase in the change in targeted exercise intensity, on average, than exercising alone does. This cause-and-effect conclusion can be made with method I because each volunteer was randomly assigned to one of two treatments. With method II, the participants are not randomly assigned to the treatments. Therefore, a cause-and-effect conclusion is not appropriate."}] :scoring {:total-points 4 :rubric [{:part "a" :max-points 2 :criteria ["The correct population for method I" "The correct justification for method I" "The correct population for method II" "The correct justification for method II"] :scoring-notes "Essentially correct (E) if the response contains all four components. Partially correct (P) if the response contains only two or three of the four components. Incorrect (I) if the response does not satisfy the criteria for E or P."} {:part "b" :max-points 2 :criteria ["The cause-and-effect conclusion is correctly described in the context of the problem, with justification based on random assignment of treatments"] :scoring-notes "Essentially correct (E) if the cause-and-effect conclusion is correctly described in the context of the problem, with justification based on random assignment of treatments. Partially correct (P) if the response indicates that a cause-and-effect conclusion is possible because randomization of treatments was used, but the response does not put the solution in the context of this problem, OR if the response indicates that a cause-and-effect conclusion is possible but does not mention random assignment as the justification. Incorrect (I) if the response does not satisfy the criteria for E or P."}]}} :reasoning "This question tests students' understanding of experimental design concepts, specifically the difference between experiments and observational studies. Method I is an experiment because it uses random assignment of treatments, allowing for cause-and-effect conclusions. Method II is an observational study because participants self-select their groups, only allowing for association conclusions. The population of generalization depends on how the sample was selected - Method I can only generalize to volunteers willing to participate, while Method II can generalize to all people at the fitness center due to random sampling."} {:id "U3-PC-FRQ-Q02" :type "free-response" :prompt "A survey was given to a random sample of 400 people living in a certain community. The people were asked whether they supported the construction of walking trails in the community park. The results are shown in the following table.\n\n| Response | Frequency |\n|----------|----------|\n| Yes, support | 210 |\n| No, do not support | 90 |\n| No opinion | 100 |\n| Total | 400 |\n\n(a) Complete the following segmented bar chart to show the relative frequencies of the results.\n\nA follow-up study will be conducted with a sample of 20 people from the 300 people who responded yes (support) and no (do not support). Two sampling methods have been proposed: a simple random sample and a stratified random sample with the survey response as strata.\n\n(b) If the stratified random sample is used, what is the number of people that will be selected from those who responded yes? Support your answer by showing your work.\n\n(c) Describe a statistical advantage of using the stratified random sample instead of the simple random sample for the follow-up study." :solution {:parts [{:part-id "a" :description "Complete the following segmented bar chart to show the relative frequencies of the results." :response "The segmented bar chart should show three segments with the following relative frequencies: 'Yes, support' = 210/400 = 0.525 (52.5%), 'No, do not support' = 90/400 = 0.225 (22.5%), and 'No opinion' = 100/400 = 0.25 (25%)." :attachments {:chart-type "bar" :x-labels ["Survey Response"] :series [{:name "No opinion" :values [0.25]} {:name "No, do not support" :values [0.225]} {:name "Yes, support" :values [0.525]}] :chart-config {:stacked true :y-axis {:min 0 :max 1.0 :tick-interval 0.1 :title "Relative Frequency"} :x-axis {:title "Survey Response"} :grid-lines {:horizontal true :vertical false} :description "Segmented bar chart showing relative frequencies of survey responses about walking trail construction"}}} {:part-id "b" :description "If the stratified random sample is used, what is the number of people that will be selected from those who responded yes? Support your answer by showing your work." :response "The proportion of adults from the sample of 300 adults who responded to the survey and indicated they support the construction of the walking trails is \\(\\frac{210}{300} = 0.7\\). Therefore, to ensure that each adult has an equal chance of being selected for the in-depth study, 14 adults must be selected from those who responded yes, because \\((0.7)(20) = 14\\)." :calculations ["Total people who responded yes or no: 210 + 90 = 300" "Proportion who responded yes: 210/300 = 0.7" "Sample size for follow-up: 20" "Number from 'yes' group: 0.7 × 20 = 14"]} {:part-id "c" :description "Describe a statistical advantage of using the stratified random sample instead of the simple random sample for the follow-up study." :response "A statistical advantage of using the stratified random sample instead of the simple random sample is that it allows for representation of the two survey responses to be in identical proportion to the responses of the 300 people who responded yes (support) and no (do not support). A simple random sample may produce a sample that will not be in identical proportion to the responses of the 300 people who responded yes (support) and no (do not support). For example, a simple random sample may produce a sample of 20 adults who responded the same way."}] :scoring {:total-points 4 :rubric [{:part "a" :max-points 1 :criteria ["Lines drawn at appropriate places in the graph" "Appropriate labels provided for segments in the graph"] :scoring-notes "Essentially correct (E) if the response includes both components. Partially correct (P) if the response includes only one of the two components. Incorrect (I) if the response does not satisfy the criteria for E or P."} {:part "b" :max-points 2 :criteria ["Response indicates the correct value (14) AND work to support the calculation"] :scoring-notes "Essentially correct (E) if the response indicates the correct value AND work to support the calculation. Partially correct (P) if the response indicates the correct value but uses weak work to support the calculation. Incorrect (I) if the response does not indicate a correct value."} {:part "c" :max-points 1 :criteria ["Response provides a reasonable statistical advantage of using the stratified random sample relative to the simple random sample in the context of potential variability across survey responses"] :scoring-notes "Essentially correct (E) if the response provides a reasonable statistical advantage of using the stratified random sample relative to the simple random sample in the context of potential variability across survey responses. Partially correct (P) if the response indicates that stratification allows for better representation in the sample but DOES NOT address variation across responses. Incorrect (I) if the response does not satisfy the criteria for E or P, including giving only vague statements such as 'data are more accurate' or 'stratified random sampling is better'."}]}} :reasoning "This question tests students' understanding of graphical representations of categorical data and sampling methods. Part (a) requires creating a segmented bar chart showing relative frequencies. Part (b) tests proportional allocation in stratified sampling - the sample must maintain the same proportion as the population (70% yes, 30% no). Part (c) examines the key advantage of stratified sampling: guaranteed representation of all strata in the correct proportions, reducing sampling variability compared to simple random sampling which might over- or under-represent certain groups by chance." :attachments {:table [["Response" "Frequency"] ["Yes, support" "210"] ["No, do not support" "90"] ["No opinion" "100"] ["Total" "400"]]}} {:id "U3-PC-MCQ-A-Q01" :type "multiple-choice" :prompt "Kristen is investigating the opinions of students at her high school on the new school hours proposed by the school board. Which of the following is her population of interest?" :answer-key "C" :reasoning "Kristen is investigating the opinions of the students at her high school, so her population of interest is all the students at her high school. The population of interest is the entire group about which we want to draw conclusions, which in this case is specifically the students at her particular high school, not a broader or different group." :attachments {:choices [{:key "A" :value "All members of the school board"} {:key "B" :value "All teachers at her school"} {:key "C" :value "All students at her high school"} {:key "D" :value "All students in the school district"} {:key "E" :value "All high school students in the state"}]}} {:id "U3-PC-MCQ-A-Q02" :type "multiple-choice" :prompt "A sample of students will be selected from all the students at a high school. Which of the following sampling methods is least likely to produce a representative sample of the students?" :answer-key "E" :reasoning "Such a method will probably overrepresent fans of basketball and underrepresent other subgroups of students. This sampling method introduces selection bias because it only includes students who attend basketball games, which is not representative of all students at the school. Students who don't attend basketball games would be systematically excluded from the sample." :attachments {:choices [{:key "A" :value "From a list of all student names, randomly select 50 names from the list for the sample."} {:key "B" :value "Randomly choose five classrooms in the school and use all the students in those classrooms for the sample."} {:key "C" :value "Divide the students into the four class years (freshman, sophomore, junior, senior) and randomly select students from each year in proportion to the number of students in each year."} {:key "D" :value "From a numbered list of all student names, randomly choose a starting point and then choose every tenth student on the list."} {:key "E" :value "From a randomly chosen home basketball game, choose every tenth student who enters the gymnasium."}]}} {:id "U3-PC-MCQ-A-Q03" :type "multiple-choice" :prompt "A teacher at a culinary arts school will conduct an experiment to investigate which of three methods of instruction works best in teaching students how to make a good pie crust. Each student in a group of 60 students will be randomly assigned to one of three methods: in-person demonstration by the instructor, watching a video, and reading a recipe. The students will be assigned so that each method will have 20 students. Each pie crust made will be judged on its taste and texture. What are the treatments of the experiment?" :answer-key "B" :reasoning "Treatments are the experimental conditions to be compared in the experiment and are applied to subjects, so the treatments are the three methods of instruction that are applied to the 60 students. In experimental design, treatments are the different conditions or interventions that researchers deliberately impose on the experimental units (subjects) to observe their effects." :attachments {:choices [{:key "A" :value "The 60 students"} {:key "B" :value "The three methods of instruction"} {:key "C" :value "The 20 students within each group"} {:key "D" :value "The scores on taste and texture"} {:key "E" :value "The 60 pie crusts made"}]}} {:id "U3-PC-MCQ-A-Q04" :type "multiple-choice" :prompt "The manager of a shopping mall distributed a customer-satisfaction survey by handing it to people as they came through one of the doors to the mall one day. Of those handed out, 215 were completed and returned. Should the results of the survey be generalized to the population of all customers of the shopping mall?" :answer-key "D" :reasoning "It is only appropriate to make generalizations about a population based on samples that are randomly selected from the population. The sample described here is not a random sample, so the results should not be generalized to the population of all customers of the mall. This convenience sampling method introduces bias since it only captures customers entering through one door on one specific day." :attachments {:choices [{:key "A" :value "Yes, because the sample size is large."} {:key "B" :value "Yes, because only people entering the mall were given the survey."} {:key "C" :value "Yes, because the sample was representative."} {:key "D" :value "No, because a random sample from all customers of the shopping mall was not selected."} {:key "E" :value "No, because not all customers were selected."}]}} {:id "U3-PC-MCQ-A-Q05" :type "multiple-choice" :prompt "Which of the following is a benefit to using a random sample for an observational study?" :answer-key "C" :reasoning "Random samples are usually representative of the population and results can be generalized. The key benefit of random sampling is that it allows for valid statistical inference - we can generalize findings from the sample to the broader population because random sampling minimizes bias and ensures that the sample is likely to be representative of the population." :attachments {:choices [{:key "A" :value "The random sample allows for different treatments to be assigned."} {:key "B" :value "A causal relationship can be determined."} {:key "C" :value "The results of the observational study can be generalized to the population."} {:key "D" :value "A random sample is the easiest method of data collection."} {:key "E" :value "The distribution of the sample will match the distribution of the population."}]}} {:id "U3-PC-MCQ-A-Q06" :type "multiple-choice" :prompt "Matt wants to investigate the opinions of young adults in the country, ages 18 years to 25 years, about time spent playing video games. He plans to administer a survey to a sample of people. Which of the following samples is most likely to generalize to his population of interest?" :answer-key "A" :reasoning "Such a sample will be most representative of all people in the country in the targeted age-group. Since Matt's population of interest is young adults in the country aged 18-25, a nationwide sample of this age group would be most representative and allow for the best generalization. The other options introduce various forms of bias by focusing on specific subgroups that may not represent all young adults." :attachments {:choices [{:key "A" :value "A nationwide sample of people ages 18 to 25"} {:key "B" :value "A sample of attendees of a gaming convention"} {:key "C" :value "A sample of people ages 18 to 25 in Matt's hometown"} {:key "D" :value "A sample of people who click on a link in an online gaming site"} {:key "E" :value "A sample of people who buy video games from an online store"}]}} {:id "U3-PC-MCQ-A-Q07" :type "multiple-choice" :prompt "The president of a small company needs to collect data on the educational background of all 20 of the company's employees. Which of the following is the best method to use for data collection?" :answer-key "A" :reasoning "Because information is needed on the population of all employees, a census should be taken. When the population is small (20 employees) and it's feasible to collect data from every member, a census is the most appropriate method. This ensures complete and accurate information about the entire population without any sampling error." :attachments {:choices [{:key "A" :value "A census"} {:key "B" :value "A cluster sample"} {:key "C" :value "A simple random sample"} {:key "D" :value "A stratified sample"} {:key "E" :value "A systematic random sample"}]}} {:id "U3-PC-MCQ-A-Q08" :type "multiple-choice" :prompt "To estimate the size of a typical housing unit in a certain town, a sociologist plans to use a cluster sampling method to gather data. Which of the following describes a cluster sampling method?" :answer-key "C" :reasoning "Cluster sampling involves dividing the town into nonoverlapping regions, selecting some of the regions at random, and then recording the sizes of the housing units in each of the selected clusters. The nonoverlapping geographic regions are the clusters. In cluster sampling, the population is divided into groups (clusters), some clusters are randomly selected, and all units within the selected clusters are included in the sample." :attachments {:choices [{:key "A" :value "Randomly select a certain number of housing units in the town."} {:key "B" :value "Divide all housing units into three groups: small, medium, and large. Then randomly select a certain number from each group."} {:key "C" :value "Divide the town into nonoverlapping regions. Randomly select from the nonoverlapping regions, and select all housing units in those regions."} {:key "D" :value "Obtain a listing of all housing units currently for sale in the town, and use the size information given in the listing."} {:key "E" :value "Obtain the records kept by the town of all housing units in the town, and use the information in those records."}]}} {:id "U3-PC-MCQ-A-Q09" :type "multiple-choice" :prompt "A certain store has 3,000 employees working at its main location in a city and 100 employees working at a smaller location outside the city. The store manager will select a sample of 50 employees from all the employees to ask their opinions about extending store hours during the holidays. What is the advantage of selecting a stratified random sample, with location as strata, instead of a simple random sample?" :answer-key "B" :reasoning "Other sampling methods could result in underrepresentation of the opinions of the 100 employees at the smaller location. The use of a stratified sample ensures that the opinions of the employees at both locations will be considered. With a simple random sample, there's a risk that few or no employees from the smaller location would be selected, leading to underrepresentation of that group." :attachments {:choices [{:key "A" :value "The stratified sample assures the most random selection from among all selection methods."} {:key "B" :value "The stratified sample assures that the opinions of employees from both locations will be represented."} {:key "C" :value "The stratified sample will be less expensive to implement than a simple random sample and will save money over time."} {:key "D" :value "The stratified sample assures employees that store hours will not be extended until their opinions are recorded."} {:key "E" :value "There is no real advantage to stratifying because a simple random sample is always the best."}]}} {:id "U3-PC-MCQ-A-Q10" :type "multiple-choice" :prompt "A certain company has five departments, A, B, C, D, and E. The number of employees in each department is 10, 10, 20, 30, and 30, respectively. A sample of 10 employees from all employees will be selected. Of the following descriptions of sampling procedures, which is most likely to introduce a potential source of bias?" :answer-key "A" :reasoning "If the sample consists of employees from department C only, then responses from the department C employees are systematically favored over responses from employees in other departments. This creates severe selection bias as it completely excludes four of the five departments, making the sample unrepresentative of the entire company." :attachments {:choices [{:key "A" :value "Randomly select 10 employees from department C"} {:key "B" :value "Randomly select 10 employees from all 100 employees"} {:key "C" :value "Randomly select 2 employees from each of the five departments"} {:key "D" :value "Randomly select 1 employee from each of A and B, 2 employees from C, and 3 employees from each of D and E"} {:key "E" :value "Randomly select every tenth employee from a randomized list of names of all employees"}]}} {:id "U3-PC-MCQ-A-Q11" :type "multiple-choice" :prompt "A scientist studying soil acidity collected soil samples from a plot of land with a stream running through it. The soil samples came from land located on only one side of the stream. What is the potential source of bias that might result from the sampling method?" :answer-key "B" :reasoning "A portion of land has been excluded from providing soil samples, so there is undercoverage of the land in the samples collected. The soil acidity in the sample collected by the scientist may not be representative of the soil acidity of the entire plot because of undercoverage bias. Undercoverage occurs when some members of the population are inadequately represented in the sample." :attachments {:choices [{:key "A" :value "Voluntary response bias"} {:key "B" :value "Undercoverage bias"} {:key "C" :value "Nonresponse bias"} {:key "D" :value "Response Bias, where responses are self-reported"} {:key "E" :value "Response Bias, where the question wording is leading or confusing"}]}} {:id "U3-PC-MCQ-A-Q12" :type "multiple-choice" :prompt "A survey will be sent to dog owners to investigate their opinions on multiple topics. Which of the following questions on the survey is most likely to contribute to question-wording bias?" :answer-key "B" :reasoning "The judgmental question wording leads the reader to respond in a way that makes them seem responsible. If the reader were to answer no, they would be indicating that they are not responsible. Answering yes will verify that they are responsible. The question will encourage answers of yes, even though the response may not be true. The word 'responsible' creates a leading question that pushes respondents toward a particular answer." :attachments {:choices [{:key "A" :value "How many dogs do you own?"} {:key "B" :value "Should responsible dog owners purchase pet insurance?"} {:key "C" :value "How much money do you spend on dog food each year?"} {:key "D" :value "How many times did you take your dogs to a vet last year?"} {:key "E" :value "Does your dog sleep in your bed on a regular basis?"}]}} {:id "U3-PC-MCQ-B-Q01" :type "multiple-choice" :prompt "A company famous for its nacho-flavored corn chips has developed two new formulas, A and B, which they hope their customers will like even more than the original formula. To determine whether customers prefer one of the new formulas over the current nacho flavoring, a sample of 50 customers is obtained. Each customer tastes both formula A and formula B in a randomly assigned order and indicates which one they prefer more. Which of the following best describes this study?" :answer-key "B" :reasoning "The study is comparative but does not include the control group necessary to meet the intent of the study. The goal is to determine whether customers prefer one of the new formulas over the current nacho flavoring, but the study only compares the two new formulas (A and B) against each other, not against the original formula that serves as the control." :attachments {:choices [{:key "A" :value "This study is not well designed because there is no replication. Each customer tasted the formulas only once."} {:key "B" :value "This study is not well designed because formulas A and B are not compared with the original formula."} {:key "C" :value "This study is not well designed because the sample may not have been randomly selected."} {:key "D" :value "This study is not well designed because each customer should taste the two new formulas in the same order."} {:key "E" :value "This study is not well designed because there is not enough replication with only 50 customers."}]}} {:id "U3-PC-MCQ-B-Q02" :type "multiple-choice" :prompt "Thirty-six students at a local middle school were randomly selected to participate in a taste test to select a new menu item for a cafeteria. Each student was given a choice between the macaroni and cheese and the Cajun potato barrels. From the sample, 20 students selected macaroni and cheese and 16 students chose the Cajun potato barrels. Each student was asked to rate the item they chose on a scale from 1 (extremely dislike) to 9 (extremely like). Which of the following prevents this study from being a well-designed experiment?" :answer-key "B" :reasoning "Students were allowed to self-select their treatment—the new menu item. Random assignment of treatments to experimental units, a key component of a well-designed study, is lacking. For a proper experiment, treatments must be randomly assigned to participants rather than allowing participants to choose their own treatment." :attachments {:choices [{:key "A" :value "There was no replication because students did not eat both menu items."} {:key "B" :value "The treatments (new menu item) were not randomly assigned to the students."} {:key "C" :value "An item that is currently on the menu should have been used as a control."} {:key "D" :value "Students should not have been randomly selected."} {:key "E" :value "There were no problems, and the study was a well-designed experiment."}]}} {:id "U3-PC-MCQ-B-Q03" :type "multiple-choice" :prompt "Diane wanted to demonstrate which pruning technique was best for controlling the growth of certain types of shrubs. She selected ten shrubs of the same type and randomly assigned each one to receive one of ten different pruning methods. Two weeks after pruning, she measured the regrowth, in inches, of the shrubs; the pruning method that minimized regrowth was recommended as the best method. Which of the following best describes why this is not a well-designed experiment?" :answer-key "C" :reasoning "Replication is required in order for an experiment to be well-designed. The experimental units are the ten shrubs, and the treatments are the ten pruning methods. The assignment of treatments to experimental units results in only one shrub for each pruning method, so there is no replication of experimental units in each treatment group. Without replication, it's impossible to distinguish between treatment effects and random variation." :attachments {:choices [{:key "A" :value "The shrubs were not randomly selected."} {:key "B" :value "Pruning methods were not randomly assigned to shrubs."} {:key "C" :value "Each pruning method was used on only one shrub."} {:key "D" :value "Each shrub did not receive all ten pruning methods."} {:key "E" :value "Only two treatments should be used in an experiment."}]}} {:id "U3-PC-MCQ-B-Q04" :type "multiple-choice" :prompt "A researcher conducted a study investigating the effect of computer screen time on a person's amount of sleep. The researcher randomly assigned 100 people into four groups. The first group was given 2 hours of computer screen time each day, the second group was given 4 hours each day, the third group was given 6 hours each day, and the fourth group was given 8 hours each day. The study was conducted for one week, and the amount of sleep for each person was measured. What is the explanatory variable in the study?" :answer-key "B" :reasoning "The amount of computer screen time is being manipulated by the researcher. The explanatory variable (also called the independent variable) is the variable that is manipulated or controlled by the researcher to observe its effect on the response variable. In this experiment, the researcher is controlling the amount of screen time to see how it affects sleep, making screen time the explanatory variable." :attachments {:choices [{:key "A" :value "The amount of sleep"} {:key "B" :value "The amount of computer screen time"} {:key "C" :value "The 100 people in the study"} {:key "D" :value "The four groups in the study"} {:key "E" :value "There is no explanatory variable because the study is observational."}]}} {:id "U3-PC-MCQ-B-Q05" :type "multiple-choice" :prompt "A researcher randomly selected 30 people to participate in a study to investigate which of two materials, A or B, used in the heels of sneakers will last longer. The researcher is considering two design types for the study.\\n\\nI. Design 1: Randomly assign 15 participants to wear sneakers with material A on their left feet and material B on their right feet. The remaining participants will wear sneakers with material B on their left feet and material A on their right feet.\\n\\nII. Design 2: Randomly assign 15 participants to wear sneakers with material A on both feet and the remaining participants to wear sneakers with material B on both feet.\\n\\nWhich of the following best describes each design?" :answer-key "B" :reasoning "Design 1 is a matched pairs design because each person is considered a pair and receives both types of materials, with the type of material randomly assigned to the left or right foot. This controls for person-to-person variation. Design 2 is a completely randomized design because the type of material is randomly assigned to each person, with each person receiving only one treatment." :attachments {:choices [{:key "A" :value "Design 1 is a completely randomized design, and design 2 is a matched pairs design."} {:key "B" :value "Design 1 is a matched pairs design, and design 2 is a completely randomized design."} {:key "C" :value "Design 1 is a matched pairs design, and design 2 is a matched pairs design."} {:key "D" :value "Design 1 is a completely randomized design, and design 2 is a completely randomized design."} {:key "E" :value "Design 1 is a completely randomized design, and design 2 is a randomized block with materials as blocks."}]}} {:id "U3-PC-MCQ-B-Q06" :type "multiple-choice" :prompt "An experiment compared the adhesion of 2 types of paint, A and B, to 3 types of metal, 1, 2, and 3, used in automobiles. Thirty sheets of metal were used in the experiment: 10 of Metal 1, 10 of Metal 2, and 10 of Metal 3. Half of each metal type will receive paint A and the other half will receive paint B. The adhesion of the paints was measured, and the measures were compared. How many experimental units are in the experiment?" :answer-key "D" :reasoning "This is the number of experimental units. It is the total number of sheets to which the treatments (type of paint) are applied. The experimental units are the individual sheets of metal, and there are 30 sheets total (10 of each metal type), so there are 30 experimental units." :attachments {:choices [{:key "A" :value "2"} {:key "B" :value "3"} {:key "C" :value "10"} {:key "D" :value "30"} {:key "E" :value "60"}]}} {:id "U3-PC-MCQ-B-Q07" :type "multiple-choice" :prompt "The two graduates with the greatest GPA from each of 14 randomly selected law schools were recruited to investigate a new method of preparation for a law exam. For each school, one student was randomly assigned to prepare using the standard method and the other student was assigned to prepare using the new method. At the end of the preparation, all 28 students were given the same exam, and their scores were recorded. Which of the following best describes why a matched-pairs design is an appropriate design for the investigation?" :answer-key "E" :reasoning "The graduates were matched within the law school they attended, and each pair received both methods (treatments). The matched-pairs design is appropriate because students from the same law school are likely to be more similar to each other than to students from different schools, so pairing within schools controls for school-related factors that might affect exam performance." :attachments {:choices [{:key "A" :valu