ctiveness of an herbal medication for pain relief, a researcher randomly selected 80 patients who were undergoing physical therapy while recovering from an injury. Of the patients, 40 had knee injuries, 16 had arm injuries, and 24 had foot injuries. The researcher will use two treatments for the investigation: the herbal medication and a standard medication. After the patients are on the medication for two weeks, the amount of pain reduction will be measured for each patient. Which of the following best describes why a randomized block design is appropriate for the investigation?" :answer-key "D" :reasoning "The type of injury is a blocking variable, and treatments will be randomly assigned within the blocks. Blocking ensures that units within each block are similar with respect to the blocking variable, and helps to separate natural variability due to the blocking variable. Different injury types may respond differently to pain medication, so blocking on injury type controls for this source of variation." :attachments {:choices [{:key "A" :value "The 80 patients were selected at random from all patients undergoing physical therapy while recovering from an injury."} {:key "B" :value "The sample size was greater than 30."} {:key "C" :value "Each patient will be randomly assigned to either the herbal medication or the standard medication."} {:key "D" :value "Blocking on injury type will help to separate natural variability from differences due to injury type."} {:key "E" :value "Each patient assigned to the herbal medication will be paired with a patient assigned to the standard medication."}]}} {:id "U3-PC-MCQ-B-Q10" :type "multiple-choice" :prompt "A professor at a large university plans to conduct a study to compare the effect of online texts versus regular printed texts on student learning. If the findings are to be generalized to all students at the university, which of the following must be part of the design?" :answer-key "B" :reasoning "A random sample of students from the university is most likely to be representative of the student population, which allows for generalizing the results. Without a random sample, the results may not be generalizable to the broader university population due to potential selection bias." :attachments {:choices [{:key "A" :value "The students in the study should have experience using online and regular texts."} {:key "B" :value "The students in the study should be a random sample from the population of students at the university."} {:key "C" :value "The students should be allowed to choose which type of text they would like to use so that different learning styles are taken into consideration."} {:key "D" :value "The professor should collect data from all students in the population before generalizing results."} {:key "E" :value "Only volunteer students should be used in the study because they are more likely to be active participants."}]}} {:id "U3-PC-MCQ-B-Q11" :type "multiple-choice" :prompt "A researcher conducted an experiment to investigate the effectiveness of a medicated lotion in treating a skin irritation. A group of 80 people with a history of skin irritation volunteered for the study. Of the 80 people, 40 were randomly assigned the medicated lotion, and the remaining 40 were given a nonmedicated lotion. At the end of one month, the skin irritation had cleared for 36 people (90 percent) using the medicated lotion and 16 people (40 percent) using the nonmedicated lotion. Analysis of the results showed the difference was statistically significant. What can be concluded from the experiment?" :answer-key "D" :reasoning "Statistical significance means that the differences in results were too large to be attributed to chance alone. Because the treatments were randomly assigned, there is evidence to conclude that the medicated lotion was more effective than the nonmedicated lotion in clearing the skin irritation. The random assignment of treatments allows for causal inference about the effectiveness of the medicated lotion." :attachments {:choices [{:key "A" :value "Treating the skin irritation with the medicated lotion will cause the irritation to clear."} {:key "B" :value "There was no difference in the effectiveness of the two lotions because 28 people still had the skin irritation."} {:key "C" :value "Any conclusion is problematic because the participants were volunteers and were not randomly selected from the population."} {:key "D" :value "There is enough evidence to conclude that the medicated lotion is more effective than the nonmedicated lotion in treating the skin irritation."} {:key "E" :value "Of the people whose skin irritation cleared, the difference between the two groups was only 20 people, which is too small for a generalization."}]}} {:id "U3-PC-MCQ-B-Q12" :type "multiple-choice" :prompt "The owner of a plant nursery will conduct a study to investigate whether a new fertilizer is more effective than an older fertilizer in helping the growth of young tomato seedlings. The owner selects a simple random sample of 50 young tomato seedlings from all the young tomato seedlings in the nursery. Half of the selected seedlings will be randomly assigned to receive the new fertilizer, and the remaining seedlings will receive the older fertilizer. The growth of the seedlings will be recorded for the next month. What is the main reason in the study for selecting a simple random sample from the population?" :answer-key "D" :reasoning "A simple random sample is likely to be representative of the population and will allow results to be generalized to the population. The purpose of random sampling is to ensure that the sample is representative of the larger population of interest, which enables generalization of the experimental results to that population." :attachments {:choices [{:key "A" :value "A simple random sample should be used to obtain all experimental units."} {:key "B" :value "A simple random sample allows for the random assignment of treatments to experimental units."} {:key "C" :value "The simple random sample allows the researcher to establish a causal relationship among the treatments."} {:key "D" :value "A simple random sample selected from the population allows the results to be generalized to the population."} {:key "E" :value "The study was observational, so a simple random sample was not needed."}]}}]}